"slag", " ash" and "superplastic" have indeed higly unbalanced because of large number of zero values. "age" is also right skewed because of outliers. Multiple modes exist for the last 4 attributes mentionned. Other attributes are pretty well distributed. The target attribute "strenght" is very well balanced and displays a relatively nice normal distribution.

Observations :

  • superplastic decrease with water
  • water increases with the presence of fly ash
  • there are some linear relationships between ash and slag for non-null values
  • age is increasing with strenght, reaching a "plateau" after a specific age

1.3 Features Engineering¶

Based on the previous analysis, we observed that categorical output can be created from the current database for the four following variables: age, slag, ash and superplastic. We will create the categories by binning each feature.

In [765]:
# binning superplastic 
# 4 categories to be created : no superplastic, 0<superplastic<6, 6=<superplastic<10, superplastic>=10 
bin_plastic_edges=[-1,0.1,6.4,10.2,32.2]
bin_plastic_names=['null','low','mid','high']
# defining a new dataframe df_plastic_bin with bining of superplastic  
# df_plastic_bin=df_age_bin
df_plastic_bin=df
df_plastic_cut=pd.cut(df['superplastic'],bin_plastic_edges,labels=bin_plastic_names)
df_plastic_cut.head(10)

# binning 'ash' 
# based on previous statistics, 'ash' can have a binary output : with (>0) and without ash (=0)
# we use the method .where() to replace the non null values by 1 
df_plastic_bin['ash'].where(df_plastic_bin['ash']==0, other=1, inplace=True)

New feature extraction¶

We can observe that coarseagg and fineagg are both dealing with the quantity of aggregates, depending on the size (coarse or fine) of the aggregate . The range of density values based of the aggregate size look indeed pretty complementary (between 594kg/m3 and 945kg/m3 for corse aggregate, between 801kg/m3 and 1145kg/m3 for coarse aggregate). Let's see if we can extract a new feature from those variables (the total density of aggregates) and check if we can drop the variables dealing with the size.

Decision on the complexity of the model¶

We may be prone to "curse of dimensionnality" issues by using simple linear regression models: there are maybe too many dimensions and the algorithm won't be able to learn.
A too complex model could also lead to overfitting. A linear regression model will be tried first to see its performance for the continuous target variable.

2. Create models and tuning it¶
